      <h3>Monday 31st August 2015 Release notes</h3>
      <div>
	<p>There are some very important changes in this package.  Here are the highlights:</p>
	<strong>Update your websites!</strong>
	<p>The fILL URL will be changing.  The new URL will be:  http://fill.mb.libraries.coop/   You can update your links right now, although for the moment the new URL simply redirects to the existing one.</p>
	<strong>Patron Authentication</strong>
	<p>Your patrons used to be required to create an account on the fILL system in order to do their own searching and requesting.</p>
	<p>Patrons will now use their barcode and PIN (or username and password) from their accounts on your ILS, just as they do with Overdrive.  fILL does not store any patron-identifying information other than the barcode (or username) the patron uses to authenticate.</p>
	<p>This major update puts control over your patron’s accounts back in your hands – if you disable or block a patron account in your ILS, that patron will also be unable able to log in to fILL (again, just like with Overdrive).</p>
	<p>Existing patron accounts on fILL will not be automatically updated;  new, non-personally-identifying accounts get created the first time patrons log in using the new authentication method.  Patrons will not be able to access the old accounts, but library staff can still see the information.  Old accounts will still exist (for the library’s benefit) until any currently active ILLs associated with the account are completed.</p>
	<p>As with Overdrive, SIP2 is the standard authentication method.  If your ILS does not have a SIP2 server, fILL has some work-arounds which will still let your patrons authenticate.</p>
	<p>It is important that you create a “test” user in your ILS, and verify that the user can log in to your library OPAC’s “My Account” section.  Send your test patron barcode/PIN to PLS@gov.mb.ca with your library name and the phrase "test patron", and we will ensure that patron authentication is set up in fILL for your library. Once authentication is configured for your library, you can go into Account > Settings > Test Patron at any time to verify that authentication is working correctly.</p>
	<strong>Individual library z39.50 profiles</strong>
	<p>Z39.50 profiles – how fILL searches your catalogue, which indexes are available, and so on – were previously grouped by ILS vendor.  This led to some issues where different libraries were on different versions of a given vendor’s product.</p>
	<p>fILL now has a separate z39.50 profile for each library.  This will enable us to individually adjust how fILL interacts with the idiosyncrasies of your z39.50 server.</p>
	<strong>Monthly ILL Board Report</strong>
	<p>A new, simple report on your ILL borrowing and lending in any given month will let you give consistent, easily understandable information at your board meetings.</p>
	<p>Under the hood, this uses the brand-new fILL statistics and fILL charting modules.  This is the first of many new reports under development, and we certainly invite feedback!</p>
	<p>You’ll find the new report under Reports > Board report.</p>
	<strong>Borrowers/Lenders Report</strong>
	<p>The new Borrowers/Lenders report will let you see which libraries you’ve been borrowing from and which you’ve been lending to, broken out by month or collapsed into a yearly total.</p>
	<p>You’ll find this report under Reports > Borrowers/Lenders.</p>
	<strong>“Lost” items</strong>
	<p>Borrowing libraries can now use a new “Lost” override (in Current > Borrowing) to indicate that an item has been lost.  Lenders will see this show up on a new list (Lending > Lost);  once the borrower and lender have made whatever arrangements they need, the lender can close the ILL transaction from the Lost list, and it will move to history.</p>
	<strong>Cancelling Renewal requests</strong>
	<p>Borrowers can now cancel a renewal request if the lender has not yet responded to it.  This puts the request back into the borrower’s Returns list, so it can be marked as returned.</p>
	<strong>Cancelling Holds placed</strong>
	<p>Lenders can now cancel a hold they've placed. This puts the request back into the lenders Respond list, so they can either reply to the borrower with a "fill" or "can't fill" (or re-place the hold with a different expected date).</p>
	<strong>LARGE PRINT indication in search results</strong>
	<p>Books catalogued as large print, either by setting the 007 field (position 1=’t’, 2=’b’) or the 008 field (position 24=’d’), or setting the 650$a=”Large type books.” will now show a “LARGE PRINT” indication in the search results.  Large print titles will show up separately from regular print, which means that if there are multiple lenders for a given large print title, they will be grouped together.</p>
	<strong>Medium (a.k.a. Format) and RDA</strong>
	<p>In the search results, Medium is now RDA-aware.  fILL will now look first for the RDA “digital file characteristics”, secondly for the RDA “carrier”, and finally fall back on the pre-RDA “general material designation” it used to use.</p>
	<strong>Borrowing overrides cleanup</strong>
	<p>Some actions which used to be borrowing overrides – “try next lender”, “no further sources”, and “cancel” – have been integrated into normal borrowing workflows.</p>
      </div>

